    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:47732968-f7da-4d66-9ed5-89a17cf78b8a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 55-year-old man who appears somewhat tired but remains neatly dressed and attentive during conversation. He has a medium build with a mildly overweight body habitus and carries himself like someone accustomed to working long hours. Over the past several weeks he has noticed a burning discomfort in the upper abdomen, worse after coffee, late-night meals, and occasional alcohol use. He describes intermittent nausea, occasional non-bloody vomiting, early satiety, bloating, frequent belching, reduced appetite, and a sour taste in his mouth, but denies obvious gastrointestinal bleeding. On exam he looks mildly uncomfortable, often resting a hand over his epigastrium, though he is not in acute distress.\n\nHe works as an operations supervisor for a regional warehouse, a role that involves irregular meal timing, frequent stress, and long sedentary stretches at a desk mixed with periods on the floor. His diet tends to be practical rather than ideal—fast food during shifts, spicy takeout a few times a week, and several cups of coffee daily. He usually drinks 1–2 beers on weekends and smokes cigars socially a few times per month but does not use illicit drugs. He tries to stay active by doing yard work and occasional weekend fishing, though he no longer exercises regularly because of fatigue and work demands.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his spouse and keeps close contact with two adult children who live nearby. He is generally independent in all activities of daily living and prides himself on rarely missing work. Friends describe him as reliable and stoic, which fits with his tendency to downplay symptoms until they interfere with sleep or appetite. Recently, his abdominal discomfort has made him more irritable and less interested in social dinners because eating often worsens the pain and he has been leaving portions unfinished.\n\nHe reports that the current symptoms began gradually and have become more frequent, especially when he takes over-the-counter ibuprofen for knee and back aches after physical chores. He has not had significant weight loss, progressive dysphagia, or black stools, but he is concerned because the discomfort keeps returning. His presentation is consistent with uncomplicated gastritis, likely influenced by dietary irritants, intermittent NSAID exposure, H. pylori infection, and stress-related symptom amplification."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:84d001b8-fc22-4ed9-8fa6-31c20ec92da3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of hypertension, dyspepsia with intermittent reflux symptoms, and chronic mechanical knee and low-back pain related to years of physically demanding work and intermittent home projects. He has no known history of peptic ulcer disease, liver disease, inflammatory bowel disease, or gastrointestinal malignancy. He reports prior episodes of stomach irritation after NSAID use but has never undergone upper endoscopy before the current evaluation. Prior hospitalizations have been limited to a brief admission for dehydration from viral gastroenteritis several years ago.\n\nHe uses ibuprofen several times per week for musculoskeletal pain, especially after yard work, which is a relevant risk factor for gastric mucosal irritation. He drinks coffee daily and typically skips breakfast, then eats larger meals later in the day. Alcohol intake is modest but regular on weekends. He does not smoke cigarettes daily but admits to intermittent social cigar use. Over the last month he has had nausea with occasional non-bloody emesis, frequent belching, and decreased appetite, but he has not noticed hematemesis, melena, or significant unintentional weight loss.\n\n{patientName} remains fully functional at home and at work, though recent abdominal discomfort has led him to reduce spicy foods and over-the-counter pain medicine. He has no prior abdominal surgeries. Preventive care has been somewhat inconsistent because of his work schedule, though he does attend primary care visits for blood pressure follow-up.\n\nFamily history is notable for his mother having chronic gastritis in her 60s and a maternal aunt with peptic ulcer disease attributed to Helicobacter pylori. This family pattern, while not determinative, adds context for upper gastrointestinal vulnerability alongside his own NSAID exposure and dyspeptic symptoms."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
